    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-06-03T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-06-03T14:00:00-05:00" n="1014"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1014">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.731/604</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_PWH1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-06-03T19:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 3 1915 7 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received June 4, 10.35 a. m</hi>.] </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2223. Your 1626, May 29, and my 2209, June 1.<note n="1" xml:id="d1014fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> Foreign Office now informs me that after another careful
                    investigation, censor cannot trace telegrams in question. States that British
                    Government will <pb facs="0976" n="718" xml:id="pg_718"/> pass all messages
                    between North and South America sent via United Kingdom, but that such messages
                    are liable in a certain degree to be held up by accident. I suggest that persons
                    in the United States desiring to send commercial messages to South America be
                    advised to use if possible a cable route which does not touch Great Britain or
                    her possessions.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">American Ambassador</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
